01:15:32.330 --> 01:15:36.480
-Oh, so those of you who don't
know, Yik Yak is a mobile app.

01:15:36.480 --> 01:15:38.330
It is sort of like
anonymous Twitter,

01:15:38.330 --> 01:15:40.940
that you can say things
anonymously and it can get up

01:15:40.940 --> 01:15:43.440
or down voted by the
rest of your community.

01:15:43.440 --> 01:15:46.310
And it's geolocated, meaning
that generally you're

01:15:46.310 --> 01:15:48.350
seeing Yik Yaks from
people around you.

01:15:48.350 --> 01:15:50.790
So I work at Fordham
University, I often

01:15:50.790 --> 01:15:53.260
look at the Fordham Yik Yak.

01:15:53.260 --> 01:15:57.200
And also it's been accused of
being used for bullying a lot,

01:15:57.200 --> 01:15:59.580
so Yik Yak has tried to put
all these really interesting

01:15:59.580 --> 01:16:01.605
technical affordances
to police user behavior,

01:16:01.605 --> 01:16:03.980
like you're not supposed to
mention other people by name,

01:16:03.980 --> 01:16:06.320
and they geofence
off the boundary.

01:16:06.320 --> 01:16:08.700
So my apartment is close
to a secondary school,

01:16:08.700 --> 01:16:10.599
so I can't use Yik Yak
within my apartment

01:16:10.599 --> 01:16:12.432
because it thinks I'm
a high school student.

01:16:12.432 --> 01:16:13.780
All right, whatever.

01:16:13.780 --> 01:16:18.350
I think anonymous internet
communication is interesting.

01:16:18.350 --> 01:16:20.954
I think that it affords
some very positive things.

01:16:20.954 --> 01:16:22.370
Quite frequently
there is evidence

01:16:22.370 --> 01:16:24.578
that people find it easier
to share with other people

01:16:24.578 --> 01:16:27.430
when they're not having
their information tied back

01:16:27.430 --> 01:16:30.847
to a singular identity, tied
to their marketing profile.

01:16:30.847 --> 01:16:32.430
And I think it is
important for people

01:16:32.430 --> 01:16:34.860
to have places to
express things that they

01:16:34.860 --> 01:16:36.300
can't express in other places.

01:16:36.300 --> 01:16:37.806
On the other hand,
I think it's also

01:16:37.806 --> 01:16:39.430
a place where people
can express things

01:16:39.430 --> 01:16:41.220
that are very offensive
or problematic

01:16:41.220 --> 01:16:43.160
or might really
hurt somebody else.

01:16:43.160 --> 01:16:45.743
And the thing about Yik Yak is
they'll give personal data over

01:16:45.743 --> 01:16:47.850
to law enforcement without
even thinking about it.

01:16:47.850 --> 01:16:49.050
That's one of their things.

01:16:49.050 --> 01:16:53.812
If you, say, Yik Yak, oh,
I want to bomb the school,

01:16:53.812 --> 01:16:55.770
they'll give that over
to the cops and the cops

01:16:55.770 --> 01:16:59.780
will arrest that person and
that's happened several times.

01:16:59.780 --> 01:17:04.010
So I go back and forth.

01:17:07.410 --> 01:17:10.400
I don't believe that
technology is neutral at all.

01:17:10.400 --> 01:17:13.370
I believe that technology
can and does express

01:17:13.370 --> 01:17:14.950
its own politics and values.

01:17:14.950 --> 01:17:17.610
And the people
behind Yik Yak seemed

01:17:17.610 --> 01:17:22.160
like their ideal was to create
something for self-expression.

01:17:22.160 --> 01:17:24.050
I don't know, what's
your opinion of Yik Yak?

01:17:24.050 --> 01:17:24.615
I would be curious.

01:17:24.615 --> 01:17:25.275
-I don't have Yik Yak.

01:17:25.275 --> 01:17:26.020
-You don't have Yik Yak?

01:17:26.020 --> 01:17:27.310
-I deleted it a while ago.

01:17:27.310 --> 01:17:30.930
-Does it have influence
on your campus?

01:17:30.930 --> 01:17:36.460
-Yes, but I try not to see it.

01:17:36.460 --> 01:17:37.230
-Yeah.

01:17:37.230 --> 01:17:39.130
But I do know that
there's been a lot

01:17:39.130 --> 01:17:42.900
of other similar, anonymous,
campus-based things

01:17:42.900 --> 01:17:43.400
in the past.

01:17:43.400 --> 01:17:45.316
There used to be something
called JuicyCampus,

01:17:45.316 --> 01:17:46.770
which was a gossip.

01:17:46.770 --> 01:17:48.210
People like to gossip.

01:17:48.210 --> 01:17:49.990
College students love to gossip.

01:17:49.990 --> 01:17:51.174
People like to gossip.

01:17:51.174 --> 01:17:53.590
that People are going to use
social media sites to gossip.

01:17:53.590 --> 01:17:56.110
I'm not sure whether I would
say that the negative effects

01:17:56.110 --> 01:17:58.197
of anonymity outweigh
the positive effects,

01:17:58.197 --> 01:17:59.780
but I think it is
important for people

01:17:59.780 --> 01:18:01.890
to have anonymous spaces online.

01:18:01.890 --> 01:18:03.470
-As a researcher
I think it's also

01:18:03.470 --> 01:18:06.160
important-- people are
always performative.

01:18:06.160 --> 01:18:08.546
They're putting on a
persona on Facebook,

01:18:08.546 --> 01:18:09.920
they're putting
on one right now.

01:18:09.920 --> 01:18:12.320
As we talk to each other,
we're doing a persona.

01:18:12.320 --> 01:18:14.170
And it's interesting
to me to be able to see

01:18:14.170 --> 01:18:17.820
some of these people who are
often fairly nasty on Yik Yak,

01:18:17.820 --> 01:18:20.480
but the chance to actually see
what they're seeing in a way

01:18:20.480 --> 01:18:22.840
that they will not
show me as an authority

01:18:22.840 --> 01:18:26.320
figure from the establishment
to know what's going on.

01:18:26.320 --> 01:18:29.440
So I don't find much of the
discussion very pleasant,

01:18:29.440 --> 01:18:32.390
but I guess I do like to know
what people are talking about.

01:18:32.390 --> 01:18:35.430
And in the end
end, that, I think,

01:18:35.430 --> 01:18:37.010
is an important
facet quite apart

01:18:37.010 --> 01:18:39.676
from the separate question of is
it beneficial or harmful, which

01:18:39.676 --> 01:18:42.270
is not so obvious.

01:18:42.270 --> 01:18:48.620
-Since we have four more
questions let's move on.

01:18:48.620 --> 01:18:51.060
-I'm writing a history of
the Equal Rights Amendment

01:18:51.060 --> 01:18:54.880
in graphic novel form, which
ends up being really look

01:18:54.880 --> 01:18:58.340
at the citizenship
of women and men

01:18:58.340 --> 01:19:00.210
and the history of
it in this country.

01:19:00.210 --> 01:19:02.400
And one of the things you
notice in the early on

01:19:02.400 --> 01:19:05.100
is that there is a
very deliberate attempt

01:19:05.100 --> 01:19:06.995
to create spheres--
the women will operate

01:19:06.995 --> 01:19:08.620
in the domestic sphere
and the men will

01:19:08.620 --> 01:19:10.030
operate in the public sphere.

01:19:10.030 --> 01:19:14.530
And so it's interesting to
look at how men talk publicly

01:19:14.530 --> 01:19:17.460
about politics and about
sports, and you often

01:19:17.460 --> 01:19:20.280
find, of course, they
talk about them similarly,

01:19:20.280 --> 01:19:22.020
that they're the teams.

01:19:22.020 --> 01:19:23.830
And I've noticed
as someone who is

01:19:23.830 --> 01:19:28.660
a woman who talks publicly about
politics, I get policed by men.

01:19:28.660 --> 01:19:31.900
And I also get women who write
to me and say, oh my god,

01:19:31.900 --> 01:19:34.100
thank you for saying
that publicly.

01:19:34.100 --> 01:19:35.880
And then I get little
secret messages.

01:19:35.880 --> 01:19:38.430
And I have lots of
little background forum

01:19:38.430 --> 01:19:41.680
of women reassuring each other.

01:19:41.680 --> 01:19:44.460
And a friend of mine, a man,
wrote a piece supporting

01:19:44.460 --> 01:19:46.500
Hillary Clinton, which
went kind of viral,

01:19:46.500 --> 01:19:48.749
and he said he got lots of
messages from women saying,

01:19:48.749 --> 01:19:50.000
thank god I had this to share.

01:19:50.000 --> 01:19:52.374
I was afraid to say I supported
Hillary Clinton because I

01:19:52.374 --> 01:19:55.020
didn't want to get yelled at,
but I could share this and be

01:19:55.020 --> 01:19:56.685
like, look, this guy likes her.

01:19:59.200 --> 01:20:02.460
So it's funny to compare the
women talking about shopping

01:20:02.460 --> 01:20:04.800
publicly and then the
harassment that women

01:20:04.800 --> 01:20:06.400
get for talking publicly.

01:20:06.400 --> 01:20:09.779
How much of that is about are
women talking in the background

01:20:09.779 --> 01:20:10.820
that we don't know about?

01:20:10.820 --> 01:20:13.209
How much of that is
affecting each other

01:20:13.209 --> 01:20:14.250
and what they talk about?

01:20:17.470 --> 01:20:19.800
-Does anyone want
to tackle that one?

01:20:19.800 --> 01:20:22.250
-I think the different
platforms are very different,

01:20:22.250 --> 01:20:25.000
so you're communicating with
your friends over Facebook

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:28.056
is very different from
publishing in a blog,

01:20:28.056 --> 01:20:30.430
and very different from being
in a gaming community which

01:20:30.430 --> 01:20:33.310
are notoriously competitive,
would be a polite way

01:20:33.310 --> 01:20:34.400
to put it.

01:20:34.400 --> 01:20:37.820
So I think that there are many,
many different communities

01:20:37.820 --> 01:20:40.870
and each person participates
in them in different ways,

01:20:40.870 --> 01:20:43.740
and it's very hard to
generalize across them.

01:20:43.740 --> 01:20:45.740
-One of the things that
we found in our research

01:20:45.740 --> 01:20:49.420
with young people is that
young people will often

01:20:49.420 --> 01:20:53.424
use a multiplexity of
different apps to communicate,

01:20:53.424 --> 01:20:55.090
and they'll often
have one of those apps

01:20:55.090 --> 01:20:57.589
will act as a sort of safety
valve, which is where they feel

01:20:57.589 --> 01:20:59.900
that they can be more honest.

01:20:59.900 --> 01:21:02.520
And quite often that's
because either they're

01:21:02.520 --> 01:21:04.740
using a pseudonym on
a site like Tumblr,

01:21:04.740 --> 01:21:08.560
or they're communicating with
a smaller group of people,

01:21:08.560 --> 01:21:10.740
like they have a group text
on WhatsApp or something

01:21:10.740 --> 01:21:13.240
and that's where they share
their more intimate feelings.

01:21:13.240 --> 01:21:15.730
But thing about
that is then you're

01:21:15.730 --> 01:21:17.490
not participating
in what we would

01:21:17.490 --> 01:21:19.030
think of as the "public sphere.

01:21:19.030 --> 01:21:21.488
And what we see historically
in the history of the internet

01:21:21.488 --> 01:21:24.160
is that men's speeches tended
to be more in the public sphere.

01:21:24.160 --> 01:21:25.620
That the blogs
written by men were

01:21:25.620 --> 01:21:28.915
valued more than the online
journals written by women,

01:21:28.915 --> 01:21:30.540
and when people are
talking about who's

01:21:30.540 --> 01:21:32.910
participating in the
kind of online punditry

01:21:32.910 --> 01:21:34.410
that we see on
sites like Medium,

01:21:34.410 --> 01:21:37.290
oftentimes it's men who are
going into those spaces.

01:21:37.290 --> 01:21:39.150
So I think that there
is certainly a value

01:21:39.150 --> 01:21:42.530
placed on where people are
participating and talking

01:21:42.530 --> 01:21:43.215
about things.

01:21:43.215 --> 01:21:44.840
And I do think that
the fact that there

01:21:44.840 --> 01:21:47.330
is this systematic
discouragement of women

01:21:47.330 --> 01:21:49.100
speaking in these sort
of internet public

01:21:49.100 --> 01:21:52.080
spheres-- I think that's a
very significant problem.

01:21:52.080 --> 01:21:52.739
I really do.

01:21:52.739 --> 01:21:54.780
I think it's a devaluing
of women's contributions

01:21:54.780 --> 01:21:57.360
to the political sphere,
to the public sphere,

01:21:57.360 --> 01:22:00.711
and frankly I think it's
a problem with democracy.

